rred roller brush spray paint used often just conventional paint with finish matching cabinet's original paint many games had artwork which was silkscreened directly on cabinets others used large decals for side art some manufacturers produce replication artwork for popular classic games—each varying quality this side art can be applied over new paint after has dried these appliques can be very large must be carefully applied avoid bubbles wrinkles from developing spraying surface with slightly soapy water solution allows artwork be quickly repositioned if wrinkles bubbles develop like window tinting applications control panels bezels marquees acquiring these pieces harder than installing them many hobbyists trade these items via newsgroups sites such ebay same true for side art with side art some replication art shops also produce replication artwork for these pieces that indistinguishable from original some even surpass originals quality once these pieces are acquired they usually snap right into place if controls are worn need replacing if game popular they can be easily obtained rarer game controls are harder come by but some shops stock replacement controls for classic arcade games some shops manufacture controls that are more robust than originals fit variety machines installing them takes some experimentation for novices but are usually not too difficult place monitors raster monitors are easier service than vector monitors normally unless main tube blown raster monitor will provide good display characteristics with perhaps few minor color adjustments vector monitors on other hand can be challenging very costly service some can't be repaired at all they have dwindled use since 1980s parts are hard come by sometimes they will have be replaced completely but even finding replacement monitors difficult since few if any are produced any longer bare new crts are still available from some suppliers vector monitors use same basic tube raster just with different electronics but they are bare tubes they usually require yoke be removed from old tube fitted new tube setting up which isn't usually job that can be undertaken by amateur arcade collector retrofitting other monitor technologies emulate vector graphics can also be done some electronic components are stressed by hot cramped conditions inside cabinet electrolytic capacitors dry out over time many classic arcade cabinets their service life nearing end if game has its original raster monitor will usually need be re-capped—that some capacitors will need be replaced so monitor will deliver proper image due size capacitors voltages present inside video monitor this can be dangerous activity should only be attempted by experienced hobbyists professionals if monitor broken replacement can usually be obtained via coin-op distributors parts suppliers wiring if cabinet needs rewiring some wiring kits are available over internet experienced hobbyist can usually solve most wiring problems through trial error many cabinets are converted be used host game other than original these cases if both games conform jamma standard process simple other conversions can be more difficult but some manufacturers such nintendo have produced kits ease conversion process nintendo manufactured kits convert cabinet from classic wiring vs wiring diy projects some cabinets are constructed entirely by hobbyists mimic arcade cabinet using emulators such mame pc replace game hardware these home built cabinets have many features real arcade cabinets such coin box marquees etc mame arcade units can combine several arcade controls such two types joysticks trackball one unit enable play many different games other projects can involve converting regular single game arcade cabinet into mame cabinet eliminating need for building cabinet dream authentics company which creates custom cabinets which run off computer run multiple games at least one company manufactures flat-pack style cabinet kits made from medium-dens